post_text:
WCUSD#15 Community

I wanted to inform you we were made aware of a COVID-19 positive student at WJHS today. The quarantined student and teacher are feeling fine and showing no symptoms.

All parties who have come into contact with the student through school activities have been notified by the district or Sangamon County Department of Public Health. They were informed and are restricted from all district activities for a period of 14 days from the time of initial contact with the student.

Thank you for your understanding and ongoing cooperation with our COVID-19 prevention policies and procedures as we work to help protect your children, your families, and our staff and their families.

Thank you

Tip Reedy -WCUSD#15 Superintendent

post_text:
WCUSD#15 Families

Today, we learned of a WHS Hybrid Learning Student tested positive for COVID-19.

We have been in contact with the Sangamon County Department of Public Health.

Contact tracing has started locally and with the health department.

The students and staff who have been in close contact (6 feet for 15 minutes throughout the day) will be contacted and quarantined for 14 days.

For your review, I have attached a formal notice of the situation.

School will resume as normal Tuesday, September 8, 2020.

Please continue to be mindful of your personal mitigation efforts.

Working together will allow us all to stay safe and healthy.

Please let me know if you have any questions.

Thank you

Tip Reedy - Superintendent
https://drive.google.com/file/d/15e8lQLVemsoIzclmMWPEQBlnZ7bWNw7q/view?usp=sharing

District Dispatch June 2020

WHAT WILL SCHOOL LOOK LIKE IN THE FALL

I want to encourage parents and families to be prepared for three types of school in August (In-person “normal school”; Remote Learning School; Hybrid School.) In the next three weeks school districts are supposed to be receiving guidance and direction from the Centers For Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), Illinois State Board of Education (ISBE) and the Illinois Department of Public Health (IDPH). I believe schools are made for social connections not social distancing.

Click here to read more...

post_text:
With Deepest Sympathies

WCUSD#15 Community,

It is with a heavy heart that I share this message with our community about a recent tragic accident that resulted in the death of Brody Wilson, a sophomore at Williamsville High School. Brody grew up in our community and was the son of Steve and Carla Wilson. He was one of five siblings and a very outgoing young man. Brody was active in student life at WHS and participated in soccer, fine arts, and band. Brody was a hard worker who loved everyone. Our thoughts and prayers go out to Steve and Carla Wilson and their family.

https://drive.google.com/file/d/1dedbxAl8AEj-TXeEqmZsLYjJZI7dcQdB/view?usp=sharing

If you have specific instructional questions, please keep doing a great job communicating with your child's teachers.

We appreciate the communities understanding, flexibility, and cooperation during these challenging times.

Williamsville-Sherman CUSD #15
March 18 at 6:57 PM ·

Good Afternoon Williamsville & Sherman Communities!

As many of you are aware, the $40million dollar WCUSD#15 facility plan referendum was overwhelming approved at the March 17, 2020 Primary Election.

I wanted to take the time to THANK the Williamsville and Sherman Communities for coming together to support a facility plan that will provide opportunities for our students and solidify the district’s facilities for the future.

The Board of Education will continue to be good financial stewards to the taxpayers.

We are very fortunate to live in these two wonderful communities and raise our families.

Our communities demonstrated we value education and we value opportunities for all students.

Even on a rainy day – The sun still shines on WCUSD#15

GREAT SCHOOLS = GREAT COMMUNITIES

Everyone Keep Being Awesome!

IT’S A GREAT DAY TO BE A BULLET AND A BEE BEE!

Williamsville-Sherman CUSD #15
March 17 at 12:46 PM ·

Thank you Williamsville Subway!

As we all know, Illinois has closed schools temporarily in an attempt to control the spread of COVID 19. In addition, restaurants are only able to operate for drive thru, curbside pickup, and delivery.

We believe this is the right decision, but also understand that it may present challenges to families in our community. We're here to help.

If you are concerned about ensuring your children have lunch, please call us and order a kids meal free of charge. Kids meals consist of a mini sub (turkey, ham, roast beef, or veggie) a side item, and 20oz. fountain drink.

Williamsville Subway # (217) 566-4324

We want to do our part to make sure our community gets through this.

#preparednotscared #nohungrykids

Valid at all Jacksonville, White Hall, Chatham & Williamsville Subways.

post_text:
Good evening Williamsville & Sherman Families,

We sure have had an interesting last few days. I am so proud of everyone’s understanding and compassion for our school district.

We still have a very important and historic opportunity for your school district. Tomorrow is Election Day.

I want to remind all families there is an important ballot issue for your school district. We encourage all of our parents and families to learn about the referendum and to vote in the election tomorrow.

The referendum is a plan to improve all of our schools throughout the district. This proposal will maintain our district’s commitment to providing the type of up-to-date facilities our children need and our families expect.

The facility plan is a smart financial improvement plan that will not change the district’s overall tax rate. These facility improvements can be made with zero change in the property tax rate to support our district.

Happy St. Patrick’s Day Tomorrow
Tomorrow is Election Day
Please Remember To Vote

GREAT SCHOOLS = GREAT COMMUNITIES

IT’S A GREAT DAY TO BE A BULLET AND A BEE BEE!

post_text:
WCUSD#15 Parents and Families

WCUSD#15 will be closed March 17 through March 30. All school events and activities will be canceled during this time.

WCUSD#15 will have school on March 16.

Monday March 16, students should take home the school supplies they may need to help them learn at home.

At this time, we plan to resume school on March 31.

We appreciate your flexibility, cooperation, and understanding during this challenging time.

text:
WCUSD#15 Parents and Families

WCUSD#15 will be closed March 17 through March 30. All school events and activities will be canceled during this time.

WCUSD#15 will have school on March 16.

Monday March 16, students should take home the school supplies they may need to help them learn at home.

At this time, we plan to resume school on March 31.

We appreciate your flexibility, cooperation, and understanding during this challenging time.

IT'S A GREAT DAY TO BE A BULLET AND A BEE BEE!

District Dispatch March 12 2020

WCUSD#15 Zero Tax Rate Change Facility Plan:
One Hundred Percent Need; Zero Percent Tax Rate Change; Benefits All Families

Tuesday, March 17, 2020, the registered voters and the residents of Williamsville and Sherman CUSD#15 will be asked to approve a proposal to provide funding for the WCUSD#15 Zero Tax Rate Change Facility Plan.
In schools that thrive in communities such as ours, we educate the students of each other’s neighbors, friends, and family members. Such close-knit relationships result in high expectations for our schools as well as the educational programming and services we provide, and justifiably so. The WCUSD#15 Zero Tax Rate Change Facility Plan is a way for the communities of Williamsville and Sherman to provide opportunities for our students, enhance, upgrade, and build district facilities so that our students may learn in a quality educational environment for many years to come.

Just The Facts!
Five Facts about WCUSD#15’s
Zero Tax Rate Change Bond Proposal

1.) All school buildings will be improved.
In order to create and increase student opportunities with classroom additions, keep abreast of best practices in education with STEM (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) labs and renovated instructional spaces, and make needed investments in district fine arts and athletic facilities, all schools in the Williamsville Sherman CUSD #15 district will be improved. This proposal will maintain our district’s commitment to providing the highest quality educational experience our children need and our families expect.

post_text: The EIU Jazz festival offered an opportunity for high school jazz bands from the region to compete in front of a panel of judges in order to receive constructive feedback. Williamsville earned first place in their class this year, an honor they have received seventeen times in the past nine years at similar festivals across the state. Many individual musicians from the band were recognized for their playing as well. Jack Yearley, Sanjay Mahinda, Chase Webb, Marissa Carrell, and Wyatt Cole were all recognized for their outstanding individual performance, while Jackson Kirkland was awarded for being the “most outstanding” musician of the day. #bulletpride
